&gt; SOLUTION:  My solution was to edit SetupCantera.vdproj in a text 
&gt; editor,
&gt; removing all sections referring to the CVS directories by hand.  I&#39;m 
&gt; not
&gt; very familiar with VStudio .NEt yet, so if there is a better way to 
&gt; edit
&gt; this file,  let me know.
&gt;
&gt; 2.  PROBLEM: The second small error occurs when running the script
&gt; run_examples.m in matlab.  Everything seems to be going fin until
&gt; PRANDTL2 dies with something like:
&gt; ************************************************
&gt;                 Cantera Error!
&gt; ************************************************
&gt; Procedure: equilibrate
&gt; Error:   Jacobian is singular.
&gt; Try adding more species, changing the elemental composition slightly,
&gt; or removing unused elements.
&gt;
&gt; SOLUTION:  This is  *not* an indication of a bad build.  This only
&gt; happens when PRANDTL2 is run with a variable directly after PRANDTL1,
&gt; without resetting the variable g.  Insert something like &quot;g=0;&quot; into
&gt; line 26 of run_examples.m and it will run beautifully.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; David Goodwin wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; I have just changed the Cantera version number to 1.5.5, and posted a
&gt;&gt; Windows source distribution at the sourceforge site
&gt;&gt; (cantera-1.5.5-src.zip).
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The big news: Cantera can now be completely built  from within Visual
&gt;&gt; Studio .NET, including the Python and MATLAB interfaces.  You can also
&gt;&gt; create your own binary installer programs (.msi files) and distribute
&gt;&gt; them to install Cantera (+ your own application code) on machines that
&gt;&gt; do not have Visual Studio.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Now there is no need to have cygwin (but personally I would install it
&gt;&gt; anyway), or to do anything from a command line, or to have Fortran.  I
&gt;&gt; think virtually all Windows installation problems should be gone now.
&gt;&gt; (Also, the Python location is no longer hard-wired to C:&#92;PYTHON23.)
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; The procedure is described step-by-step in a Powerpoint presentation I
&gt;&gt; have also posted at the Sourceforge site under &quot;Cantera Documentation&quot;
&gt;&gt; - see file cantera-vc7.ppt.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Other than that, you may notice a new class &quot;Mixture&quot; in Python, and a
&gt;&gt; couple of new classes (MultiPhase and MultiPhaseEquil) in C++. These
&gt;&gt; implement multi-phase mixtures and a new multi-phase equilibrium
&gt;&gt; solver.  It is fully functional in Python and C++ now (MATLAB soon),
&gt;&gt; but is not documented, so its official introduction will be in Cantera
&gt;&gt; 1.6 which will be out in January.  Cantera 1.6 will contain also some
&gt;&gt; new phase models, and some improved support for non-ideal phases.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Windows people in particular - if you have Visual C++ .NET, please try
&gt;&gt; out the new build procedure, and report any problems.
